!! A 22nd Century Constitution
!!!! Samuel Tenka, 2020 February

!!! Preface

    This is a fantasy.  It is as much romantic wish fulfillment as it is
    science-fictional speculation, and it lacks both plausibility and
    thoughtful ethical examination.  It reconciles my preferences --- for rule
    of law through textualist interpretation and for personal liberty as
    imagined in modern times --- by changing the text.  It also tries to do
    away with artifacts of a less connected age.

!! Article I: The Legislature

!!! I.a. A Bicameral Congress

!!! I.b. The House of Representatives

!!!! I.b.0. Membership, Terms, and Election
    The House of Representatives shall have $1776$ seats in
    correspondence with geographical districts so uniform
    that no district exceeds another in census-measured population by a factor
    of $21/20$.  A representative's term shall
    endure $2$ years, and no person shall serve two consecutive terms in the
    House.

    The representative for each district shall be decided as follows.
    Each Citizen of voting age whose main residence falls within that distict
    may cast one vote for one candidate.
    Meanwhile, the several candidates shall order themselves alphabetically.
    Each candidate shall privately determine a real, $20$-digit number
    $x_i \in [0, 1]$.  Before election day, they shall publically announce
    cryptographically secure hashes of their real numbers.  At the close of
    the last ballot box, the candidates shall reveal $x_i$s, and the threshold
    $X$ shall be computed as the sum of the $x_i$s mod $1$.  The votes shall
    be tallied for each candidate, then in the order determined by the
    candidates partially summed; the first candidate whose corresponding
    partial sum exceeds the threshold $X$ shall earn the seat in question.
 
    Should an unexpected vacancy arise, the Chief Executive of the relevant
    state shall appoint a temporary Representative.

!!!! I.b.1. Majority and Alternative Leaders

    At each session's start, the convening representatives shall together elect 
    a majority leader by simple unweighted majority; those senators who
    did not vote for the resulting Majority Leader shall nominate an Alternative
    Leader by simple unweighted majority.  For these votes, the
    Vice President shall resolve ties.  This process must resolve within four
    weeks.

!!! I.c. The Senate 
!!!! I.c.0. Membership, Terms, and Election
    The Senate shall have $2$ seats for each of the several States.
    A senator's term shall endure $6$ years, and no person shall serve two
    consecutive terms in the Senate.

    The Several States shall upon entrance to the Union be divided as evenly
    as possible into $3$ classes; the $i$th class shall elect one of its
    senators in a year $6n + 2i$ and the other in a year $6n + 2i+1$.
    A State's senatorial elections shall permit any Citizen of voting age whose
    main residence is that State to approve or disapprove of each senatorial
    candidate; that candidate that receives the fewest disapprovals shall earn
    the seat in question.

    Should an unexpected vacancy arise, the Chief Executive of the relevant
    state shall appoint a temporary Senator.

!!!! I.c.1. Majority and Alternative Leaders
 
    At each session's start, the convening senators shall together elect 
    a majority leader by simple unweighted majority; those senators who
    did not vote for the resulting Majority Leader shall nominate an Alternative
    Leader by simple unweighted majority.  For these votes, the
    Vice President shall resolve ties.  This process must resolve within four
    weeks.

!!!! I.c.1. Voting 
    Each seat shall, at the start of its term, 
    be allotted $1789$ points to be spent on votes. 
    A seat may vote with integer weight $n+1 \geq 0$ by spending $n^2$
    points.  No vote may cause the allotted points to fall below $0$. 
    The will of the Senate shall unless otherwise specified be determined by
    strict majority among the weighted yeas and nays; no action shall be taken
    in case of a tie.

    Members may vote 

    The Senate shall adopt no rules requiring majorities other than those here
    specified. 

